## Stage 3: Confirmatory Gate (Multiplicity-Aware)

> **Purpose:** Test each candidate in C on the holdout, with proper error control.
> **Data used:** Holdout partition only. First access to this data.
> **Decision output:** Rejection set R ⊆ C.

### Prompt 3.1 — Pre-Confirmation Protocol

```
Before accessing holdout data, finalise the test specification.

For each candidate in C, the confirmatory test is:
  Estimator:     Spearman IC (cross-sectional, per-period)
  Null:          H₀: ρ_s ≤ {ECONOMIC_SIGNIFICANCE_FLOOR}
                 (default: 0.02; this is a non-inferiority null,
                  not a point null at zero)
  Alternative:   H₁: ρ_s > {ECONOMIC_SIGNIFICANCE_FLOOR}
  Test type:     One-sided
  Test method:   Stationary block bootstrap
                 (block_len = {BLOCK_LEN}, n_boot = {N_BOOT})
  Significance:  per-test α determined by multiplicity method

Multiplicity adjustment:
  Effective tests:     M_eff = __ (from Stage 1, Prompt 1.4)
  Nominal candidates:  |C| = __
  Dependence structure: [PRDS / arbitrary / unknown]

  IF PRDS (positive regression dependence on subsets):
    Method: Benjamini-Hochberg at FDR ≤ {TARGET_FDR} (default: 0.05)
  IF arbitrary dependence:
    Method: Benjamini-Yekutieli at FDR ≤ {TARGET_FDR}
  IF FWER control preferred (selecting single best signal):
    Method: Holm-Bonferroni at FWER ≤ {TARGET_FWER} (default: 0.05)

  Optional refinement: if M_eff << |C|, use the Meff-adjusted
  Bonferroni (replace |C| with M_eff in the correction).
  Document the justification.

Researcher degrees of freedom buffer:
  If informal exploration preceded this pipeline (e.g., you looked at
  scatter plots, read papers suggesting carry works), inflate the
  effective test count: M_adjusted = M_eff × {RDF_MULTIPLIER} (default: 2)
  Document what prior exploration was done and why the multiplier is fair.

Output: a GATE CONTRACT in the format below. This contract is immutable.
```

### Prompt 3.2 — Execute Confirmatory Gate

```
Execute the confirmatory gate for research track {TRACK_ID}.

ACCESS HOLDOUT DATA NOW. This is the first and only access.

For each candidate c_i in C (i = 1, ..., |C|):
1. Compute the test statistic: Spearman IC on the holdout period
2. Compute the bootstrap p-value (one-sided, against the
   non-inferiority null H₀: ρ_s ≤ {FLOOR})
3. Record: raw_p_i, IC_estimate_i, IC_se_i, IC_95CI_lower_i

Apply multiplicity adjustment:
4. Sort raw p-values: p_(1) ≤ p_(2) ≤ ... ≤ p_(|C|)
5. Apply the pre-specified method (BH / BY / Holm):
   - Compute adjusted p-values: adj_p_i
   - Determine rejection set: R = {c_i : adj_p_i < α}

Output (structured, all fields required):
- TABLE: one row per candidate with columns:
  [candidate, IC_est, IC_se, IC_95CI_lo, raw_p, adj_p, rejected?]
- REJECTION SET: R = {list of candidates that passed}
- |R| / |C|: confirmation rate
- STRONGEST SIGNAL: candidate with lowest adjusted p-value
- IF |R| = 0: "The research track has failed at confirmation.
  No signal survives multiplicity-adjusted testing on the holdout.
  Archive the track. Do not re-test on the same holdout."

Do NOT interpret borderline results as "suggestive" or "trending."
The gate is binary: reject or fail-to-reject. Record and move on.
```

### Prompt 3.3 — Post-Confirmation Diagnostics (Holdout Data)

```
For each signal in the rejection set R (using HOLDOUT data):

A. CONDITIONAL CALIBRATION PLOT
   - Bin the signal into deciles on the holdout
   - For each decile, compute: realised hit rate (fraction of correct
     sign predictions) vs predicted hit rate (from logistic calibration
     fitted on TRAIN data and applied to holdout)
   - Plot: predicted (x) vs realised (y), with the 45° line
   - Annotate: Brier score, calibration slope, calibration intercept
   - Interpretation:
     - Points above 45° line: signal is under-confident (leaving money)
     - Points below: over-confident (position sizing will be too aggressive)
     - Flat line at ~50%: signal has no real discriminative power
       despite passing the IC test (pathological case; investigate)

B. DRAWDOWN ANATOMY
   - Compute the cumulative long-short return (Q5 − Q1) on holdout
   - Plot the equity curve
   - Below: scatter of (drawdown duration in days, drawdown depth in bps)
     for every drawdown episode
   - Annotate: max drawdown, max duration, recovery time
   - Flag: if a single drawdown accounts for >50% of the total path
     variance, the signal may be regime-dependent

C. QUANTILE SPREAD RETURN HEATMAP (repeat of 2.2B, on holdout)
   - Same construction as the training version
   - Place training and holdout versions side by side for visual
     comparison of monotonicity stability
   - Formal test: Jonckheere-Terpstra on holdout quintile means
   - Flag: if monotonicity is present in train but absent in holdout

D. TRAIN vs HOLDOUT COMPARISON TABLE
   For each signal in R, side-by-side:
   [metric, train_value, holdout_value, ratio]
   Metrics: IC, IC_se, hit_rate, Q5−Q1 spread, Sharpe, max_drawdown
   - Flag if holdout IC < 50% of train IC (signal decay)
   - Flag if holdout Sharpe < 50% of train Sharpe
```

